Activities on the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) closed positive yesterday, reversing two-day negative sentiments following gains recorded by blue chip stocks. The key market performance measures, the NSE All Share Index and market capitalisation, rose by 0.13 per cent to close the trading session positive as market sentiments returned to gaining streaks following investors’ sustained optimism on undervalued stocks. Consequently, the All-Share Index gained 34.4 basis points or 0.13 per cent to close at 26,824.50 as against 26,790.10 recorded the previous day while the market capitalisation of equities appreciated by N16 billion or 0.13 per cent to close at N12.946 trillion from N12.930 trillion as market sentiment returned on the green zone. Meanwhile, a turnover of 303.8 million shares exchanged in 3,151 deals was recorded in the day’s trading. The insurance sub-sector was the most active (measured by turnover volume); with 176.8 million shares exchanged by investors in 150 deals. Volume in the sub-sector was largely driven by activities in the shares of Law Union and Rock Insurance Plc and Mutual Benefits Assurance Plc. The premium sub-sector boosted by activities in the shares of Access Bank Plc and UBA Plc followed with a turnover of 50.9 million shares in 1,169 deals. The number of gainers at the close of trading session was 19 while decliners closed at 13. Cadbury Nigeria Plc led the gainers’ table with a gain of 10 per cent  to close at N9.90 per share while Cutix Plc followed with a gain of 9.72 per cent to close at N1.58 per share. GSK Plc added 9.65 per cent to close at N6.25 per share. On the other hand, CI Leasing Nigeria Plc led the price losers’ table, dropping 9.85 per cent to close at N5.95 per share. Jaiz Bank Plc followed with 8.70 per cent to close at 63 kobo per share while Livestock Feeds Plc trailed with a loss of 7.27 per cent to close at 51 kobo per share.